I think all three
of us have been

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:36.940
in different parts of
Harvard in different parts

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:38.920
of our careers in education.

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:43.140
So what strikes
all us, I think, is

00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:45.870
that although we want to do a
lot of focus on this-- a lot

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:48.390
of the conferences around
this instructor at the middle

00:00:48.390 --> 00:00:52.680
of this circle, that context
that the instructor is in

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:56.640
has an enormous impact on
how well that structure can

00:00:56.640 --> 00:00:57.640
perform.

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:00.080
And should we be thinking
of how to evaluate

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:01.890
the quality of the
decision making

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:03.220
that creates this context?

00:01:03.220 --> 00:01:05.136
I mean, one colleague
looked at this and said,

00:01:05.136 --> 00:01:07.096
oh, you're talking
about the culture.

00:01:07.096 --> 00:01:10.360
Yes, but it's not an
immutable culture.

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:13.230
What are some of the decisions
that-- or the ways decisions

00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:15.090
are made that
effect that culture,

00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:16.800
that create that culture.

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:19.850
So that's what we wanted to have
this group be talking about.

00:01:19.850 --> 00:01:21.690
And even thinking of
how to ask about it

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:23.799
was really quite a long process.

00:01:23.799 --> 00:01:26.257
We really appreciate the input
of the HILT people and we've

00:01:26.257 --> 00:01:29.170
all been going in
circles around this--

00:01:29.170 --> 00:01:31.790
So this is from a public
health concept called

00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:34.670
the socio-ecological
framework for health,

00:01:34.670 --> 00:01:37.432
with a patient or the
individual in the middle,

00:01:37.432 --> 00:01:39.390
but then there's all
these different influences

00:01:39.390 --> 00:01:40.410
on the individual.

00:01:40.410 --> 00:01:43.245
But we thought we'd sort of
steal from it a little bit

00:01:43.245 --> 00:01:46.200
and apply it to
teaching and talk.

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:48.330
So what I'd like for
people to talk about

00:01:48.330 --> 00:01:51.960
is how are decisions
made about these things

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:52.900
in your institutions?

00:01:52.900 --> 00:01:53.858
What's your experience?

00:01:53.858 --> 00:01:54.936
And what can be improved?

00:01:54.936 --> 00:01:56.310
Where are we--
how can we come up

00:01:56.310 --> 00:02:00.890
with a list of best practices to
improve the culture of teaching

00:02:00.890 --> 00:02:04.540
and the likelihood of success
of teaching in our schools.

00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:06.017
I'm going to very quickly.

00:02:06.017 --> 00:02:08.475
In our school, we have a set
of students whose expectations

00:02:08.475 --> 00:02:13.410
are that attendance is optional
and that they should be told

00:02:13.410 --> 00:02:16.030
what to think, because they went
to, frankly, medical schools,

00:02:16.030 --> 00:02:17.206
many of them.

00:02:17.206 --> 00:02:20.230
And no offence, but that's where
a lot of them got their habits.

00:02:20.230 --> 00:02:23.354
So just that alone has been a
real challenge for those of us

00:02:23.354 --> 00:02:24.770
that believe in a
more interactive

00:02:24.770 --> 00:02:28.874
and engaging and presence
and mind and body.

00:02:28.874 --> 00:02:30.540
In terms of how
programs are structured,

00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:32.620
you can have a program
that is actually

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:34.950
not built so that courses
build on each other

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:37.160
or that people are
overlapping or that they're

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:39.210
well-coordinated and
so the students get

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:41.190
the maximum benefit
out of whatever

00:02:41.190 --> 00:02:42.710
you're doing as an instructor.

00:02:42.710 --> 00:02:45.405
So things about how those
educational programs are

00:02:45.405 --> 00:02:47.677
designed and coordinated
is another one

00:02:47.677 --> 00:02:50.010
of the many things that can
effect the quality of what's

00:02:50.010 --> 00:02:51.599
going on in the classroom.

00:02:51.599 --> 00:02:52.390
School-wide policy.

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:55.750
We've all talked about
promotion criteria,

00:02:55.750 --> 00:02:57.340
although that may not--

00:02:57.340 --> 00:03:00.640
in our school, we find most of
our senior faculty are teaching

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:03.930
and some of that teaching
is highly variable.

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:05.900
But also how
teaching is paid for,

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:07.340
what kind of
classroom facilities

00:03:07.340 --> 00:03:10.260
are out there for
you to teach in.

00:03:10.260 --> 00:03:12.330
All kinds of different
types of decisions

00:03:12.330 --> 00:03:15.399
that effect whether you can
actually teach in the most

00:03:15.399 --> 00:03:16.440
interactive way possible.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:18.460
How well your IT systems work--

00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:20.760
your technology works.

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:24.470
Whether you have support to do
technology assisted learning.

00:03:24.470 --> 00:03:25.680
And then external forces.

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:27.280
Carolyn and I were
having a great discussion

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:29.196
at one point about the
role that accreditation

00:03:29.196 --> 00:03:32.880
plays in medical school, driving
so much of the context there.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:35.160
And licensing exams,
whereas public health

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:37.650
doesn't have that
external pressure

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:41.365
to hit the targets and measure
that learning through passage

00:03:41.365 --> 00:03:43.390
of the licensure exam.

00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:45.349
So this is the topics
we wanted to talk about.

00:03:45.349 --> 00:03:47.890
Maybe Carolyn, you want to make
a couple remarks, and Monica,

00:03:47.890 --> 00:03:49.860
too, about what you observed.

