big observation,

00:36:01.390 --> 00:36:03.270
but I would love to
hear from others.

00:36:03.270 --> 00:36:05.540
One of you had-- two
of you had hands up.

00:36:05.540 --> 00:36:06.040
In the back.

00:36:06.040 --> 00:36:08.290
I was just going to follow
up on the incentives thing.

00:36:08.290 --> 00:36:10.625
It's not only that great
teaching isn't incentivized.

00:36:10.625 --> 00:36:13.130
It's actually the reward
for great teaching

00:36:13.130 --> 00:36:13.910
is more teaching.

00:36:16.730 --> 00:36:17.230
Absolutely.

00:36:17.230 --> 00:36:19.680
And then your time.

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:23.090
And sometimes I think bad
teaching or just barely

00:36:23.090 --> 00:36:27.020
passable teaching is
incentivized because, honestly,

00:36:27.020 --> 00:36:31.160
scholarship is where promotion
and standing in the community

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:34.100
is, and honestly, should be.

00:36:34.100 --> 00:36:35.606
We are a research institution.

00:36:35.606 --> 00:36:36.980
And so if there's
a problem, it's

00:36:36.980 --> 00:36:39.500
not like we can just say, oh,
we'll realign our incentives.

00:36:39.500 --> 00:36:41.270
Teaching is really
where it's all at.

00:36:41.270 --> 00:36:43.010
Because scholarship is.

00:36:43.010 --> 00:36:45.560
And there's always so
many hours in the day.

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:46.200
I know.

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:49.175
Just something to keep in mind.

00:36:49.175 --> 00:36:50.800
I had a different
question, but now I'm

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:52.258
thinking about this
question that's

00:36:52.258 --> 00:36:54.110
the balance of research
and teaching, which

00:36:54.110 --> 00:36:57.014
is part of the incentives.

00:36:57.014 --> 00:36:58.430
I'm not sure-- it
seems like we're

00:36:58.430 --> 00:37:02.630
living during a pretty historic
period, where we are rethinking

00:37:02.630 --> 00:37:06.110
what knowledge is, whether
knowledge should be carved up

00:37:06.110 --> 00:37:08.015
into what we call
fields or disciplines

00:37:08.015 --> 00:37:11.670
or this 19th century German
model of the research

00:37:11.670 --> 00:37:12.170
university.

00:37:12.170 --> 00:37:15.740
It seems like we're still taking
that for granted at least in,

00:37:15.740 --> 00:37:16.860
I would say, in FAS.

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:18.480
I'm not sure about
other schools,

00:37:18.480 --> 00:37:20.810
so I only speak to that.

00:37:20.810 --> 00:37:24.050
And you know, I know plenty
of students personally

00:37:24.050 --> 00:37:28.310
who were baffled by
the implicit acceptance

00:37:28.310 --> 00:37:31.250
that there is a link between
research and teaching

00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:36.350
and that scholar teachers, it
feeds each other, as opposed

00:37:36.350 --> 00:37:39.830
to say taking somebody who
actually can communicate

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:42.590
and can get people to
understand a concept,

00:37:42.590 --> 00:37:44.960
even if that person is
not the best in the field

00:37:44.960 --> 00:37:47.040
or contributing new knowledge.

00:37:47.040 --> 00:37:48.980
And I wonder if that--

00:37:48.980 --> 00:37:51.170
uncoupling that or
maybe even questioning

00:37:51.170 --> 00:37:55.280
that as a kind of article
of faith in the research

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:57.350
university maybe will
help us understand

00:37:57.350 --> 00:38:00.815
that there are different people
who need different things.

00:38:00.815 --> 00:38:03.470
People who've committed
to a concentration,

00:38:03.470 --> 00:38:05.025
but then maybe
never go back to it.

00:38:05.025 --> 00:38:06.900
Go off and do something
completely different.

00:38:06.900 --> 00:38:08.441
As opposed to a
graduate student, who

00:38:08.441 --> 00:38:10.410
is committing to it for life.

00:38:10.410 --> 00:38:14.330
I know a lot of freshmen
who could care less, really,

00:38:14.330 --> 00:38:19.730
about the research element
of their professor's life

00:38:19.730 --> 00:38:23.177
and don't understand why the
teaching is not prioritized.

00:38:23.177 --> 00:38:24.610
And I just want
to build on that.

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:28.190
I want to push back a
little bit on just the depth

00:38:28.190 --> 00:38:29.840
of the focus on
research to the point

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:32.490
where it crowds out teaching.

00:38:32.490 --> 00:38:35.340
We had a dean at the Kennedy
school that used to say,

00:38:35.340 --> 00:38:36.144
we're a school.

00:38:36.144 --> 00:38:38.060
You have to remind people
that we're a school.

00:38:38.060 --> 00:38:39.460
We are not a think tank.

00:38:39.460 --> 00:38:41.135
There are think tanks out there.

00:38:41.135 --> 00:38:43.170
Harvard University
is not one of them.

00:38:43.170 --> 00:38:45.440
So if we're going
to accept students,

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:47.480
we actually do
have an obligation

00:38:47.480 --> 00:38:50.210
to do a good job in
building their skills

00:38:50.210 --> 00:38:51.680
and their progress
towards mastery.

00:38:51.680 --> 00:38:55.730
And I actually wanted to
draw a parallel to the idea

00:38:55.730 --> 00:38:57.950
that President Faust raised
about creating synergies

00:38:57.950 --> 00:39:00.000
between your research
and your teaching

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:04.510
to creating synergies
about kind of being

00:39:04.510 --> 00:39:08.582
a strong leader or a strong
citizen and your teaching.

00:39:08.582 --> 00:39:10.790
And I think that at the med
school, one of the things

00:39:10.790 --> 00:39:12.340
that struck me most
when I got there

00:39:12.340 --> 00:39:13.840
was that the way
that they've define

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:16.130
their competencies
for doctors has

00:39:16.130 --> 00:39:19.730
very little to do with factual
knowledge of hard science.

00:39:19.730 --> 00:39:23.270
I would say 80% of the
competencies fall around things

00:39:23.270 --> 00:39:26.270
like, can you ask
the right questions?

00:39:26.270 --> 00:39:28.000
Can you empathize
with your patient?

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:30.110
Are you open to
their perspective?

00:39:30.110 --> 00:39:34.510
Are you going to give
them a care routine

00:39:34.510 --> 00:39:36.650
that they can actually
comply with, based

00:39:36.650 --> 00:39:38.450
on their socioeconomic status?

00:39:38.450 --> 00:39:39.920
So these are leadership skills.

00:39:39.920 --> 00:39:41.440
These are communication skills.

00:39:41.440 --> 00:39:42.980
These a human skills.

00:39:42.980 --> 00:39:45.510
And in my view, those
things are as or more

00:39:45.510 --> 00:39:47.795
important than any factual
knowledge or research

00:39:47.795 --> 00:39:50.240
knowledge that might come out.

00:39:50.240 --> 00:39:53.870
So I would just pose
another alternative.

00:39:53.870 --> 00:39:55.540
I think we are out of time.

00:39:55.540 --> 00:39:56.840
Just-- my last observation.

00:39:56.840 --> 00:39:59.480
I teach strategy,
organizational strategy.

00:39:59.480 --> 00:40:02.570
And the one thing
that always strikes me

00:40:02.570 --> 00:40:05.050
in these conversations
is how rarely one

00:40:05.050 --> 00:40:07.640
says we have educational
goals we want to reach

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:11.460
and we have a process for
making sure that we reach them.

00:40:11.460 --> 00:40:13.390
And so much of
education is indeed

00:40:13.390 --> 00:40:15.980
this sort of organic
entrepreneurial individual

00:40:15.980 --> 00:40:18.100
faculty interest, but
does that measure up?

00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:20.202
Does that sum up
to where we want--

00:40:20.202 --> 00:40:21.660
what we want our
students to learn?

00:40:21.660 --> 00:40:23.201
And the environment
at medical school

00:40:23.201 --> 00:40:25.050
is far more required
to go that way because

00:40:25.050 --> 00:40:26.060
of the external demand.

00:40:26.060 --> 00:40:27.780
But in these softer
fields where there

00:40:27.780 --> 00:40:31.740
aren't these external
demands, it's not clear to me

00:40:31.740 --> 00:40:33.620
that the educational
goal-setting process

00:40:33.620 --> 00:40:36.577
is one that is linked to the
rest of what happens in terms

00:40:36.577 --> 00:40:38.660
of what gets offered and
how programs are designed

00:40:38.660 --> 00:40:40.010
and what courses.

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:41.630
So our --my school
really doesn't

00:40:41.630 --> 00:40:44.118
have a strategic planning
process for education.

00:40:44.118 --> 00:40:46.076
But I think-- I don't
know about other schools,

00:40:46.076 --> 00:40:48.740
but I think that's one of
the missing links for making

00:40:48.740 --> 00:40:51.792
all this sort of get and give
people reason for why they

00:40:51.792 --> 00:40:53.500
teach what they teach
that may or may not

00:40:53.500 --> 00:40:54.880
be linked to research.

00:40:54.880 --> 00:40:58.060
But this was a
fantastic conversation.

00:40:58.060 --> 00:41:00.745
It was great to hear from so
many different perspectives.

00:41:00.745 --> 00:41:03.800
Please spend time thinking
about what one thing

00:41:03.800 --> 00:41:05.585
you learned that
you hadn't already--

00:41:05.585 --> 00:41:07.660
Or one question you could ask.

00:41:07.660 --> 00:41:09.436
You could add a question.

00:41:09.436 --> 00:41:12.800
It's a sign of a good session
if you leave with questions.

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:13.460
So thank you.

00:41:13.460 --> 00:41:15.100
And we'll share back
to you by email.

00:41:15.100 --> 00:41:16.600
Thank you.

00:41:16.600 --> 00:41:18.750
[APPLAUSE]

